ladders.explanation:
This problem requires counting all square submatrices (of any size) where every element is 1. The dynamic programming approach builds a DP table where dp[i][j] represents the side length of the largest square ending at cell (i,j) with bottom-right corner at (i,j). The key insight is that if matrix[i][j] = 1, then dp[i][j] = 1 + min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]). This works because a square ending at (i,j) can only extend the minimum of squares ending at its top, left, and top-left neighbors. The sum of all dp[i][j] values gives the total count of all squares, since each dp value counts all squares ending at that cell (e.g., dp[i][j]=3 means there are squares of size 1, 2, and 3 ending there).

Algorithm: 1. Initialize dp as a copy of matrix with same dimensions. 2. For i from 1 to rows-1 and j from 1 to cols-1, if matrix[i][j]==1, set dp[i][j]=1+min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]). 3. Sum all values in dp.

Time complexity: O(n*m) where n=rows, m=cols. Space: O(n*m) for dp table, optimizable to O(m) by keeping only previous row.

Connection to L1: This uses the core recurrence relation from L1 to compute dp values.

Common mistakes: Forgetting to handle first row/col separately (they remain as matrix values), incorrect min calculation, or misunderstanding that dp sum counts all squares.

Real code pattern:
def countSquares(matrix):
    rows, cols = len(matrix), len(matrix[0])
    dp = [[0]*cols for _ in range(rows)]
    total = 0
    for i in range(rows):
        for j in range(cols):
            if matrix[i][j] == 1:
                if i==0 or j==0:
                    dp[i][j] = 1
                else:
                    dp[i][j] = 1 + min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1])
                total += dp[i][j]
    return total

This sub-routine computes dp[i][j], which represents the side length of the largest square ending at (i,j). The recurrence is: if matrix[i][j] == 0, then dp[i][j] = 0. If matrix[i][j] == 1, then dp[i][j] = 1 + min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]) for i>0 and j>0. For cells in the first row or first column (i==0 or j==0), dp[i][j] = matrix[i][j] (since they can only form squares of size 1 if value is 1).

Intuition: A square ending at (i,j) can only be as large as the smallest square among its top, left, and top-left neighbors, plus 1 for the current cell. This ensures all cells in the square are 1. The min operation guarantees the square is valid.

Algorithm: Input: matrix value m, dp_top, dp_left, dp_topleft, and flags is_first_row, is_first_col. If m==0: return 0. Else if is_first_row or is_first_col: return 1. Else: return 1 + min(dp_top, dp_left, dp_topleft).

Time: O(1). Space: O(1).

Connection to L0: This is the core computation used in the double loop of the full solution.

Common mistakes: Not handling edge cases (first row/col), using max instead of min, or not checking matrix value first.

Real code pattern:
def compute_dp_value(matrix_val, dp_top, dp_left, dp_topleft, i, j):
    if matrix_val == 0:
        return 0
    if i == 0 or j == 0:
        return 1
    return 1 + min(dp_top, dp_left, dp_topleft)
